title.narrative: 402 FAMILY/COMMUNITY BASED CARE FOR PREVENTION OF SEPARATION AND REHABILITATION

description.narrative: By 2022, key stakeholders have capacity to develop, implement and monitor family/community based care for prevention and rehabilitation of children in contact with the law, children without family care and those who are victims of violence or exploitation, which contributes to Promotion Of Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being And Justice, Promotion Of Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being And Justice (Covid), Protection From Violence, Exploitation, Abuse And Neglect. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Communications, Advocacy And Public Engagement, Community Engagement, Social And Behaviour Change, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Harnessing Power Of Business And Markets, Innovation, Partnerships And Engagement: Public And Private, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Business and Key Business Stakeholders demonstrate growing willingness, commitment and resource allocation for protecting and promoting child rights in policy and practice by 2022

description.narrative: In 15 states, UNICEF supported Government and other stakeholders in preventing family separation and family based care services. 227,862 children supported to prevent family separation and to provide alternative care in about 270 districts across 13 states. 18500 child protection functionaries capacitated on gate keeping, and case management. To prevent risks of child labour, unsafe migration and trafficking, supported government in mobilising 16,500,000 at risk families and linked them to social protection schemes; 2.5 million community members reached with key messages to prevent child labour and exploitation of children; 51 integrated district plans developed | Status:On-track | As-of Date:06/01/2022
